<TEXT>
the producers of a broadway play about arms 
control negotiations brought their performance to congress on 
monday night where it was viewed by an appreciative audience that 
included the secretary of state and two men involved in such talks 
it bore no resemblance to reality thats what made it so 
good said secretary of state george shultz after viewing a 
walk in the woods it was a good characterization and a lot of 
laughs he said 
the play starring sam waterston as the american negotiator and 
robert prosky as his soviet counterpart was performed in the 
library of congress auditorium across the street from the capitol 
a dozen senators having just finished a day of debate about the 
ussoviet mediumrange arms control treaty were among the 250 
people who attended the play along with shultz paul nitze and 
maynard glitman 
nitze was the american who formed the basis of waterstons 
character while glitman was the chief us negotiator on the 
mediumrange missile treaty 
nitze and glitman agreed with shultz 
it didnt bear any relationship to anything we talked about 
said nitze 
its a dramatization and while its good its not like 
reality said glitman 
the play a black comedy is based on nitzes 1982 private talk 
with yuri kvitsinsky nitzes soviet counterpart that discussion 
produced an agreement between the two men on the framework for a 
mediumrange missile treaty but the plan was later rejected by 
both governments 
sen claiborne pell dri chairman of the foreign relations 
committee said he thought the production dramatizes the human 
side of what is too often a faceless bureaucracy 
pell was one of the hosts for the play which was performed by 
waterston and prosky on their day off 
</TEXT>
