<TEXT>
the soviet decision to withdraw troops from 
afghanistan is more than a lifesaving step it has rescued mikhail 
gorbachev from another leavetheafghansalone lecture from 
president reagan 
as the leaders prepare for their fourth summit in moscow may 
29june 2 the first red army units have come home to uzbekistan 
and the soviets seem determined to meet a february 1989 deadline 
for the removal of all 115000 troops 
the erasure of afghanistan as the topmost regional issue at the 
summit will give reagan more time to push gorbachev toward 
settlements in other global hot spots cambodia southern africa 
the middle east and central america 
at least for now there has been a resolution or at least the 
formula for resolving the afghan issue said michael h armacost 
undersecretary of state for political affairs and head of the us 
team preparing for the summit discussion of regional issues 
at the summit there just isnt that much more to say to them 
except perhaps thanks and keep up the good work said 
another state department official speaking on condition of 
anonymity 
this official and armacost as well suggested however that 
afghan issues could reemerge as a summit topic because the united 
states and the soviet union are still actively engaged in the 
settlement process as the soviets wind down their eightyear war 
in terms of military arrangements one of our biggest concerns 
is that they take out whatever minefields they have sown over the 
past eight years the state department official said this is 
an issue of safety for civilians coming back to their villages 
earlier this year before the soviets signed a pledge to 
withdraw their troops the united states beseeched moscow to take 
the further step of ceasing military assistance to the government 
headed by afghan leader najib 
in return the united states said it would stop giving military 
support to the mujahadeen the antisoviet resistance fighters 
matching soviet restraint with us restraint 
moscow rejected the proposal and on may 14 the soviet military 
commander in afghanistan announced he would leave behind up to 1 
billion in arms and installations for use by the afghan army 
that doesnt strike me as a demonstration of tremendous 
restraint armacost said he reiterated the us determination to 
keep helping the guerrillas and said bluntly well have 
practical ways of accomplishing that purpose 
asked if gorbachev might seek reagans help in getting the 
resistance to let the russian troops retreat home without being 
harried by attacks armacost said the soviets would do better by 
seeking local arrangements with mujahadeen leaders 
though these issues remain the fundamental decision to withdraw 
and evidence last week that the agreement is being carried out 
removed an irritant that has nagged ussoviet relations since 
december 1979 when red army forces entered what had been a civil 
war 
president carter protested the invasion by keeping the us 
olympic team home from the 1980 moscow games and he embargoed grain 
sales to the soviets 
reagan resumed the grain deals but he made clear that better 
ussoviet relations hinged to a large extent on moscows 
willingness to pull its troops home from the afghan conflict 
indeed before his met gorbachev in geneva in 1985 in reykjavik 
in 1986 and in washington in 1987 he devoted speeches to the issue 
and signaled his intention to berate the soviet leader about 
afghanistan when they met 
for example in a speech to the heritage foundation eight days 
before the washington summit reagan said its time for them to 
pack up pull out and go home its time that they set a date 
certain for the complete withdrawal of all soviet troops from 
afghanistan 
reagan said it appeared that even the soviets were writing off 
the current regime in kabul the soviets pride themselves on 
recognizing objective reality well its time for them to bite the 
bullet 
by contrast two weeks before the moscow summit the white house 
found itself praising soviet actions calling the pullout a 
welcome first step 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
henry gottlieb covers the state department for 
the associated press 
