<TEXT>
a new state law allowing students to choose 
their schools will improve education proponents say but some 
educators fear the plan could hurt smaller schools and bring 
unhealthy competition 
we realize there may be some poor choicemaking in the free 
market but the challenge is to educate parents in how to make 
sound choices says nan skelton assistant state education 
commissioner 
the measure gives minnesota the nations broadest open 
enrollment plan skelton said schools may refuse students only if 
the transfer would interfere with desegregation ratios in 
minneapolis st paul and duluth or if the school is too crowded 
state funding about 3000 per youngster follows the student 
to the new district previously parents had to pay tuition to the 
new district 
gov rudy perpich signed the measure into law may 6 it takes 
effect in the 198990 school year in larger districts and applies 
statewide in 199091 
state education officials hope schools will improve their 
programs in the competition to attract students a 1986 national 
governors association project recommended open enrollment as a way 
to boost school quality 
i have mixed feelings said jeff keller an assistant to the 
superintendent of the 89student humboldtst vincent school 
district one of the states smallest if theyre put on the 
honor system are they going to transfer for the right reasons 
