james hooley has planned presidential travel 
to most of the 50 states and 18 foreign countries including the 
economic summits in tokyo and venice but president reagans trip 
to the soviet union this week was different 
preliminary preparations for the moscow summit began in 1985 
after reagan and soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev met in geneva 
and said they wanted to visit each others country 
its a whole different mind set hooley director of 
presidential advance said of the soviets they dont deal with 
the kind of things we deal with 
we are constantly pushing and urging and prodding for things 
that are just sort of anathema to their system 
for instance there was the matter of the private dinner reagan 
and gorbachev are having at a country home outside moscow 
the soviets insisted there be no press coverage hooley 
reluctantly agreed but said there should at least be an official 
photographer the soviets said no 
i cant seem to get them to grasp the concept that this is an 
incredibly historic thing or potentially historic these guys 
eating dinner out there in this house in the country hooley said 
in a recent interview it would be like having a picture of 
roosevelt and stalin 
they just dont think like that you really sense that 
instinctively theres a pullback from anything thats going to be 
other than exactly like how they do it and how theyve done it for 
