<DOCNO> AP880523-0043 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
karoly grosz hungarys new communist 
party leader has built a reputation as a canny pragmatic 
politician with a charisma not unlike that of his soviet 
counterpart mikhail s gorbachev 
grosz 57 succeeded janos kadar on sunday as general secretary 
during an overhaul of the party leadership 
after becoming premier in june grosz established himself as a 
politician willing to tackle unpleasant economic issues while 
softening the blow of austerity measures with the promise of 
political reform 
he has moved around the country chatting with workers and 
apparently enjoying interviews with journalists from the staterun 
media during a visit last month to britain he proved to be an 
unabashed admirer of prime minister margaret thatcher 
these tactics overshadowed party ideologist janos berecz 
groszs main rival in the battle to become party chief and kadar 
himself who was left to shoulder the blame for hungarys economic 
crisis 
like gorbachev who is two years his junior grosz comes from an 
impeccable background and got his start in politics during the 
turbulent times of josef stalins death in 1953 
official biographies say grosz was born into a workers family 
in 1930 in the northeastern city of miskolc 
a communist by 1945 grosz followed his mother into work in a 
print shop by 1949 he was in budapest with the national party 
youth organization 
seizing a chance for promotion and education grosz entered the 
countrys military academy in the early 1950s training as an 
officer for the hungarian army whose upper ranks had fallen victim 
to sweeping stalinist purges 
within a year grosz was a deputy lieutenant he then served as 
full lieutenant stationed near the yugoslav border who also was 
charged with the political education of his battalion 
in november 1954 grosz was discharged from the army and sent to 
borsod county party committee in northern hungary to observe party 
organizations factories and coal mines in his native miskolc 
official accounts suggest grosz spent the turbulent year of 1956 
in miskolc removed from the turmoil in budapest where kadar 
emerged as undisputed leader after soviet troops crushed an 
antistalinist revolt and arrested liberal leader imre nagy 
by 1961 grosz had moved up to the central apparatus of the 
hungarian socialist workers party after a spell at the party 
academy and was named party head at staterun radio and television 
between 1968 and 1973 grosz was deputy head of the partys 
central committee propaganda department and from 1974 to 1979 was 
in full charge of the official propaganda machine 
he returned to borsod as regional party head in 1979 and in 
december 1984 advanced to head the influential budapest party 
which contains almost one quarter of the nations 800000 
communists 
at the national party congress in march 1985 grosz was elevated 
to the ruling party politburo 
when grosz was named premier he almost immediately acknowledged 
that some political reform was needed to complement stringent 
economic measures he pushed to control mounting foreign debt 
he pushed through the east blocs first valueadded and personal 
income taxes designed to deregulate price controls and tap the 
income from the second jobs many hungarians hold to make ends meet 
although his austerity program is to last until 1990 grosz has 
stressed there is no target date for overcoming hungarys economic 
crisis 
grosz has outlined vague plans for parliament to have a larger 
and more supervisory role in government decisionmaking and even 
countenanced dialogue with unofficial opposition groups who do not 
contest communist rule 
this government is not likely to go down in history as one of 
the victorious grosz said last fall but if we can succeed we 
will be praised for taking an interest in the country 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
