two senators and an 11member coalition of 
health groups called today for increased spending on disorders that 
afflict senior citizens saying the money will be needed to cope 
with the largest senior boom in history 
the task force for aging research funding recommended that the 
nation spend 340 million above current levels on research into 
strokes alzheimers disease and other afflictions the figure is 
278 million higher than what president reagan has requested for 
fiscal 1989 which begins oct 1 
we wont be able to accomplish this budget but we ought to 
push for it said sen pete domenici rnm ranking republican 
on the senate budget committee its very practical its an 
absolute must when you look at the demographics and the cost of 
health care 
sen john melcher dmont chairman of the senate special 
committee on aging said senior citizens groups are leading the 
push for the additional spending but its for the benefit of 
those to follow since the research wont bear fruit for 10 to 20 
years 
daniel perry executive director of the nonpartisan alliance for 
aging research said onethird of the 450 billion spent annually 
on health care is on the 12 percent of the population over 65 
with no medical breakthroughs perry said by the middle of the 
next century there will be three times more hip fractures four 
times as much demand for nursing home beds and eight times as many 
cases of dementia as in 1980 
our goal is not simply a longer life span but a longer 
healthspan he said 
in its report the task force says less than 05 percent of the 
146 billion spent annually on health care for those over 65 goes 
for research to prevent and treat agerelated problems this 
represents a poor investment strategy for a nation soon to 
experience the largest senior boom in history the report said 
the number of americans over 85 currently 27 million is 
expected to double by the end of the century and quadruple in the 
next 60 years the task force said 
we can tinker with changes in the health care delivery system 
which can produce some savings but these savings will not equal 
the longterm benefits of dramatic medical and scientific changes 
that will alter the way we experience old age the report said 
the task force called for a national focus on research to help 
lower medical expenses and improve the health of older americans 
including higher investments in basic research and research 
targeted at specific diseases such as alzheimers faster clinical 
trials greater support and training for geriatric medicine and 
further study of the psychological behavioral and sociological 
aspects of aging 
the agencies receiving budget increases under the task force 
proposal would be the national institute on aging the national 
institute of mental health the national institute of neurological 
and communicative disorders and stroke the national institute of 
arthritis and musculoskeletal and skin diseases and the veterans 
administration 
