<TEXT>
the supreme court today expanded its study of 
whether payments made to the church of scientology by its members 
may be claimed as federal income tax deductions 
the justices who last month agreed to review the issue today 
added one case to its study the test case used by the us tax 
court in 1984 a supreme court decision is expected sometime next 
year 
scientologists make payments called fixed donations to the 
church 
the internal revenue service says such payments for auditing 
and training sessions are not charitable contributions that can be 
counted as tax deductions 
scientologists say the irs has singled out their church for 
unfair treatment and is interfering with their religious freedom 
federal law allows taxpayers to reduce their tax liability by 
declaring various deductions including money or things of value 
given to charities or religious organizations but such a payment 
is not taxdeductible if something of value is received in return 
a practice within the church of scientology is a process known 
as auditing in which members are expected to reach a higher level 
of spiritual awareness auditing is administered in a onetoone 
session in which the church members skin responses to questions 
are measured by an electronic device 
each branch of the church charges a fixed donation for 
training and auditing sessions and almost never waives the payment 
requirement 
the tax court ruled that the fixed donations required by the 
church are not taxdeductible contributions but instead are 
nondeductible payments made for services 
that ruling was upheld by the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
in a case involving church of scientology members katherine jean 
graham of honolulu richard m hermann of los angeles and david f 
maynard of rialto calif 
the high court today said it will use the appeal of those three 
