wtbs said in a statement the new rules do not give the cable 
industry a realistic chance to avoid massive blackouts 
turner held out the possibility of a court appeal but said that 
decision would be made after the fcc issues its written rules 
jeff treeman senior vice president of united video the tulsa 
oklabased cable carrier that distributes superstation signals 
including wgn said cable systems in some large markets where 
independents can afford to buy exclusive rights to programming may 
have to black out or substitute shows for as much as 40 percent of 
a superstations programming 
thats enough for the cable operator to drop the signal he 
said 
under the new syndicated programming exclusivity rules tv 
stations will be able to negotiate for exclusive rights to a 
syndicated program and will be able to force a cable system to 
honor that contract the rules also allow broadcasters to negotiate 
rights with cable systems 
superstations also will be able to buy exclusive rights for 
syndicated shows on a nationwide basis under the rules 
patrick said the new rules wont go into effect for one year to 
give cable systems time to prepare 
the rules wont apply to cable systems with fewer than 1000 
subscribers about half of all cable systems fall into this 
category though they serve only about 5 percent of the nations 45 
million cable subscribers the fcc said 
you will see more diversity in programs said edward o 
fritts president of the national association of broadcasters 
though he added that rules will likely drive up the cost of 
syndicated programming 
