next months communist party conference is shaping 
up to be a faceoff between supporters of radical change and 
advocates of just a little polishing up of the old soviet 
system party activists reported monday 
despite efforts by mikhail s gorbachev to draw only backers of 
his policy of perestroika or wholesale rebuilding of soviet 
society some who fear reform is being introduced too quickly may 
be selected as delegates to the june 28 conference 
a closeddoor meeting of the party central committee devoted to 
preparations for next months conference selected gorbachev to 
deliver the key address to the gathering which will pass judgment 
on his reform program the tass news agency reported 
but senior advisers on the economy and social trends made clear 
at a news conference that conflicting viewpoints on the pace of 
reform are becoming more apparent 
it has not even been decided whether the party gathering the 
first of its kind since 1941 will be televised according to 
delegate sergei p zalygin editor of the journal novy mir new 
world 
gorbachev addressed the plenary session of the central committee 
before and after a debate among the more than 300 members tass 
said no details of his or other speeches were released 
kremlin no 2 yegor k ligachev told a foreign policy meeting 
later in the day that the plenum had a very interesting and 
lively debate over the proposals to be presented at the 
conference 
ligachev has made clear in previous speeches that he favors a 
more moderate pace of reform 
the theses put together by the ruling 13man politburo make a 
number of important suggestions and proposals relative to the 
implementation of perestroika glasnost democratization and the 
implementation of a healthy political atmosphere ligachev said 
he gave no details but said the proposals will be published 
before the conference 
four of the nations most respected advisers on perestroika told 
reporters the conference is heightening differences among 
policymakers 
tatiana zaslavskaya the nations leading sociologist and a 
staunch reform advocate said if perestroika is to succeed we 
will have to fight and struggle for it to see that we meet these 
goals 
