<DOCNO> AP880523-0130 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court agreed monday to study the 
power of states to regulate natural gas production including 
useitorloseit rules designed to stimulate production 
the court will review a ruling that upheld the power of kansas 
officials to control production from what is believed to be the 
largest natural gas reservoir in the world the justices are not 
expected to decide the case until 1989 
the kansas supreme court in 1987 upheld rules adopted by the 
kansas corporation commission that officials said would encourage 
production prevent economic and physical waste and protect the 
rights of producers 
at issue is gas from the hugoton field which extends across 
portions of kansas oklahoma and texas about twothirds of the 
field is in kansas containing some 4000 wells as of 1983 most of 
the gas is carried outside the state through pipelines 
the kansas corporation commission since 1944 imposed rules aimed 
at assuring that each well will ultimately produce approximately 
the amount of gas underlying the land held by each leaseholder 
the idea was to treat well owners equally since gas can migrate 
underground from an underproducing area to a well that is 
overproducing 
to assure equal treatment the state fixed the maximum amount of 
gas that can be produced per month from each well 
in practice wells cannot always be operated to meet monthly 
ceilings for various reasons for example a well may be shut in or 
there may be low demand in a given month and therefore the well 
underproduces 
to allow for these variables state officials permitted owners 
of underproducing wells to save up their production ceilings 
creating what are called underages and overproduce in future 
months to make up for shortfalls 
to create a production incentive the kansas commission changed 
the rules in 1983 by declaring that underages must be used within 
specified periods of years or they would be canceled 
the useitorloseit rule was challenged by northwest central 
pipeline corp one of the major buyers of the hugoton gas for 
transport outside the state 
northwest central said the 1983 rule change prevents it from 
purchasing gas reserves that it is entitled to by contract the 
pipeline company said cancellation of the underages means that it 
unfairly may lose reservoirs of gas when they migrate underground 
and later are replaced by other migrating supplies 
the pipeline company asked the supreme court to strike down the 
1983 regulations on grounds that the federal energy regulatory 
commission has exclusive authority over natural gas production 
the reagan administration sided with kansas officials in urging 
the high court not to disturb the kansas supreme court ruling 
the justice department said the kansas commission lawfully is 
regulating production and is not directly regulating the interstate 
pipeline companies that are subject to federal authority 
the department said the kansas case is distinct from a decision 
by the supreme court in 1986 that added a new limitation on states 
power to regulate natural gas prices 
the court said then that mississippi may not require an 
interstate pipeline to buy gas from all owners of a common gas pool 
when the pipeline had preexisting contracts with only some of the 
owners 
the case acted on monday is northwest central pipeline vs 
kansas 861856 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

