<TEXT>
a former professor suing to become the fifth woman 
granted tenure in the harvard business schools 80year history 
testified monday that the academic guidelines were manipulated to 
deny her tenure because of her sex 
barbara bund jackson 44 who resigned in 1984 is asking us 
district judge douglas p woodlock to reinstate her with tenure and 
award 847000 in lost income 
manipulation of the tenure process and the use of review 
procedures different from those used for men are the absolute 
core of the discrimination ms jackson testified in the first 
day of her nonjury trial 
ms jackson has also charged that the school destroyed documents 
requested by her to support her claim that lessqualified men 
received tenure from 1974 to 1984 
harvard maintains in court papers that ms jacksons academic 
work was substandard and that the tenure records were unwittingly 
destroyed by someone outside the business school 
ms jackson testified she was pressured into submitting new 
examples of her scholarship sooner than it was required she also 
asserted that a faculty member threatened not to support her in her 
tenure bid because of conflicts over what material a course should 
cover 
i believe this was done with the express purpose of 
discriminating against me on the basis of sex she testified 
ms jackson was asked repeatedly to cite specific incidents of 
sex bias she alleged against several faculty members when she was 
unable to on one occasion she said 
to me bias is a spectrum and i dont know where to draw the 
line in that spectrum she said 
in court papers the school said that ms jackson was given a 
virtually unprecedented second chance after she was denied 
tenure in 1981 and that the faculty voted by just 3631 to support 
her 1983 bid a low margin a tenure committee rejected her 
tenure decisions at harvard are submitted to the faculty to 
gauge support for the professor the actual decision rests with the 
university president who receives a recommendation from the 
schools dean 
she was given an extremely thorough and fair review in 1981 
and 1983 and the decision was made entirely on her academic 
qualifications allan a ryan jr an attorney for harvard said 
in court papers 
ms jackson a marketing consultant began teaching at harvard 
as an assistant professor in 1973 she was promoted to associate 
professor in 1977 
in her first attempt at tenure she failed to win support of the 
faculty which cited inadequate scholarship ms jackson was given 
a threeyear extension on her appointment and submitted new 
academic work for review 
three of the 90 business schools tenured professors are women 
four women have received tenure in the business schools history 
the first in 1961 the school said 27 percent of the 819 students 
in the class of 1988 were women 
legal experts say few gender bias cases make it to trial and 
plaintiffs have won even fewer cases because judges are reluctant 
to rule on matters of academic merit 
nationally 72 percent of male faculty members have tenure 
compared with 45 percent of females according to a recent survey 
of 1055 two and fouryear institutions by the american 
association of university professors 
