<TEXT>
after six months in office premier li peng 
remains something of a mystery perhaps not an exciting one 
universally described as methodically attuned to solving 
problems rather than politicking the 59yearold li is generally 
regarded as bland but the kind of leader china needs to solve 
problems slowing the decadeold modernization drive 
overshadowed by his predecessor the urbane and nattily dressed 
communist party chief zhao ziyang and without power to 
singlehandedly formulate policy li has yet to offer any bold 
initiatives 
he has given few clues to his own vision of chinas future or 
his goals as premier other than reducing an 11 percent inflation 
rate 
although he is one of the five members of the communist party 
politburos standing committee chinas most powerful policymaking 
body li has been exceptionally cautious in public statements 
he remains dogged by a widely held assumption that he owes his 
job to nepotism he is the adopted son of the late premier chou 
enlai his rise to the premiership was meteoric he was appointed 
acting premier in november just eight years after being given his 
first government post minister of power 
the national peoples congress chinas legislature confirmed 
him as premier in april 
a few days later he became the target of satirical attacks in 
posters put up by students at beijing university 
if li peng can become premier who cant said one 
lis main credentials for the job were his technical skills and 
connections trained as an engineer in the soviet union he spent 
most of his career running power projects and never ran a city or 
provincial government 
after becoming minister of power in 1979 he rose in rapid 
succession to vice premier in 1983 politburo member in 1985 and 
education minister later that year as education minister he 
escaped responsibilty for the widespread prodemocracy student 
demonstrations of 198687 saving himself by denouncing liberal 
intellectuals 
many intellectuals dislike him for that and for his failure to 
improve their salaries and living conditions 
however unpopularity is the least of lis problems because 
chinas premiers are selected by party leaders not the ballot box 
he must cope with inflation that has reached its current 11 
percent from 6 percent two years ago he also must unclog chronic 
supply bottlenecks and get rid of waste in government offices and 
state factories 
but any dramatic initiatives to do all those things would need 
the approval of fellow members of the politburo standing committee 
including zhao his predecessor 
zhao had a mandate for change when he became premier in 1980 and 
many of his policies remain in force 
that leaves li with the task of trying to implement policies set 
by zhao who may not look kindly on any changes in them by an 
underling 
when li took office it was widely speculated he favored central 
planning over zhaos marketstyle reforms 
but lis comments have given no sign he opposes those reforms 
but zhaos reforms have hit snags that li now must try gingerly 
to resolve 
one is economic incentives such as bonuses for workers who 
increase productivity they were liberally distributed and had come 
to be automatic in addition the bonuses are said to have eaten 
into capital investment and helped fuel inflation 
an asian diplomat quoted chinese sources as saying li recently 
refused to approve automatic bonuses maintaining the incentives 
should be more closely linked to production increases 
that report remains to be confirmed 
but li has made city mayors responsible for decontrolling 
statesubsidized food prices 
and in a profile of lis first 130 days in office the official 
weekly magazine liaowang outlook credited him with playing a 
major role in working out a plan to streamline and reorganize the 
government bureaucracy 
