<TEXT>
from the gilded splendor of kremlin reception 
halls to a mockwestern hotel frequented by foreign businessmen and 
kgb prostitutes moscows busiest landmarks are being pressed into 
service for this weeks ussoviet summit 
president reagan soviet communist party general secretary 
mikhail gorbachev hundreds of staff workers and thousands of 
journalists will occupy just a few buildings in the city but their 
presence will be dominating 
the official meetings will take place in the kremlin seat of 
soviet power and although they dont live within the fortress 
walls the gorbachevs will give a state dinner there for the 
reagans who will be hosts for a reciprocal affair at their summit 
quarters the us ambassadors residence known as spaso house 
the official american entourage and much of the white house 
press accompanying reagan will be housed at the mezhdunarodnaya 
international hotel attached to the moscow center for 
international trade the hotel also will serve as headquarters for 
an international press corps now estimated to number at least 5000 
many of the visiting journalists will stay at the mammoth 
3200room rossiya hotel between red square and the kremlin 
although officials have said some outlying hotels also will be used 
to handle the flood of reporters photographers and technicians 
here are historical notes and descriptions of the principal 
summit venues 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the deltashaped fortress that today encloses the soviet 
government and communist party leadership behind russet crenelated 
walls dates back to the 15th century at the site of a former 
white stone kremlin 
inside the kremlin walls bordered by the moscow river red 
square and the alexander gardens that run along bustling prospekt 
marx are a jumble of czarist palaces cathedrals government 
buildings and state museums including the armory which houses 
faberge eggs gold peter the greats high boots and other kremlin 
treasures and memorabilia 
the leaders will likely meet at some time during the summit in 
the roseandsilvercolored hall of st catherine a 19th century 
remnant of the russobyzantinestyle imperial residence that is now 
the grand kremlin palace 
the most stringent security measures in a capital known for 
caution are practiced at the kremlin where the three main gates 
are manned by dozens of uniformed kgb border guards and access even 
to the roads leading up to the gates is restricted 
during the meetings and festivities connected with the summit 
the broad stretches of asphalt and cobblestone between the historic 
buildings will be black with freshly polished zil limousines used 
to shuttle soviet dignitaries as well as the american vehicles 
that will be flown in for use by reagan and his senior staff 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the yellow new empirestyle mansion which takes its name from 
the small spasopeskovskaya square out front and a nearby russian 
orthodox cathedral will house reagan his wife nancy and their 
personal staff during their fiveday stay in moscow 
the reagans will stay in the secondfloor guest quarters that 
had been known as the vice presidential suite but will be renamed 
in honor of its new guests according to us embassy press attache 
richard gilbert 
ambassador jack matlock and his wife rebecca plan to stay in 
their own quarters in the mansion for the presidential visit 
spaso house a twostory dwelling with a columned front portico 
was built in 1914 on the grounds inhabited in the 17th century by 
the czars dogkeepers and falconers its wealthy builder nikolai 
vtorov was killed shortly after the 1917 bolshevik revolution and 
the mansion was expropriated by the soviet government 
it was turned over to the united states in 1933 when william c 
bullitt arrived as the first us ambassador to the soviet union 
the mansion and its surrounding gardens have been the scene of 
raucous celebrations such as the one on christmas eve 1934 
recalled in charles w thayers book bears in the caviar when 
animals borrowed from the moscow zoo went beserk in the ballroom 
premier nikita khrushchev attended lawn parties there when he was 
still in power 
in world war ii a bomb shelter was built in the mansions 
basement and the ambassador and his staff evacuated to the volga 
river city of kuibyshev in late 1941 when german troops drew close 
to the city and air raids broke an occasional window 
the vaulted ceilings and doric columns that distinguish the 
interior are complimented by cream navy and mauve furnishings a 
collection of ultramodern art chosen by the matlocks hangs on 
the marble walls as part of the art in embassies program 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the modern slategray towers of the americandesigned hotel and 
business complex known among foreigners as the mezh is an 
island of western life that is for the most part offlimits to 
soviet citizens 
the mezh derived from the russian word mezhdunarodnaya 
meaning international is so different from most soviet business 
and residential buildings that filmmakers use the interior to 
portray american venues in the 1985 film we accuse about the 
u2 spy plane s news agency says 5000 reporters have sought 
accreditation for the summit and the white house and soviet 
foreign ministry agreed the secondfloor congress hall was the only 
place in the city that could accommodate a press center even so 
it will seat fewer than 1000 of those expected 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
twice ravaged by fire the 5500bed rossiya will serve as home 
and office for the worlds broadcast media 
television and radio teams have built studio sets on the 
westwing balconies overlooking red square and the kremlim from 
which the nightly news on all four american networks will be 
anchored 
the 12story hotel which took 25 years of haggling design 
change and behindthescenes debate to complete opened its first 
rooms in late 1966 and was completed in 1971 it has restaurants 
six bars a film theater and a concert hall 
fire struck the north wing feb 25 1977 and at least 30 people 
were killed an exploding television set in one of the rooms was 
blamed for a jan 8 1987 blaze that killed one woman 
the hotels location near the most popular sights of the soviet 
capital has made it a favorite with tourists for the past 20 years 
the familiar onion domes of st basils cathedral and a halfdozen 
small churches relocated to the site during construction projects 
around moscow stand in stark contrast to the modern steel glass 
and concrete rossiya to the north is the state department store 
gum and across red square are spassky tower the kremlin wall 
burial ground and lenins redmarble mausoleum 
