<TEXT>
on the first weekend of every 
month thousands of art lovers take a walk on the wild side through 
some of south africas loveliest farmland 
its the crocodile ramble stretching 28 miles near honeydew a 
village in the minkandmanure belt so called because of the 
areas wealthy horsekeeping inhabitants 
civil servants from government offices in pretoria businessmen 
from johannesburg and young families getting their first taste of 
serious art walk and drive along dirt trails through cow pastures 
and bush artists and craftsmen open their workshops and chat with 
all comers about form color and price 
visitors who dont buy can still enjoy coffee wine and light 
lunches bands play hotair balloons float overhead water 
sportsmen head for hartebeespoort dam a nearby lake enthusiasts 
of early humans prowl among the caves at sterkfontein a few miles 
away 
zulu tribesmen dance for tourists in a kraal of treebranch 
walls set up by a local hotel 
artists have lived for decades in the gentle hills around the 
crocodile river their thatched houses secluded but still close to 
showrooms in johannesburg 
the idea of the ramble came a year ago to potter tim morris and 
his wife marlene who specializes in bonsai 
art should be accessible to everybody including people who 
are frightened of going into a gallery children should be 
confronted with art morris said 
the problem with this society is its flush and its plastic 
people are susceptible to easy forms of entertainment beer 
rugby braais cookouts and video its essential that these 
things are counterbalanced 
morris encouraged some 25 friends to open their studios to the 
public once a month creating a vast attraction for both 
connoisseurs and tourists 
property values soared jewelrymaker debbie scrimgeour bought 
her farm for 90000 just before the ramble opened and said its 
now worth 170000 
some artists uncomfortable dealing with the public dropped 
out others welcomed their freedom from the demands of galleries 
which take up to 40 percent of selling prices and found new 
customers by taying home morris said he took in 2500 on a recent 
weekend 
in a country where nearly all human endeavors are affected by 
the prolonged conflict over apartheid the ramble remains a 
nonpolitical patch of western taste set incongruously in the 
african countryside the artists and craftsmen are white some born 
in europe some incorporate african themes in their work others 
such as morris draw on northern hemisphere traditions 
the only studio devoted to black african art was hit by 
lightning and burned down in february 
the success of white farmers and artists masks poverty among 
black seasonal farm workers residents say scrimgeour said a 1987 
survey by a local church listed 25 percent of black children under 
6 years old as dangerously malnourished she said the ramble has 
increased black employment 
the ramble includes owen wood who charges up to 3500 for his 
handforged knives woods wife sue paints on silk muralist 
mickey korzennik spent decades decorating corporate headquarters 
before he lost a contract he had pursued for a year the 
disappointment made him rethink his life and his art 
now i stay here and do what i want and let people respond 
he said his large wood and steel sculptures sell for up to 8000 
henry yatt a furniture designer and his wife fiona an 
interior decorator opened a gallery of paintings by a friend 
peter nel who died three years ago 
we had about 60 of them and at first we didnt know what to 
do yatt said now theyre being sold and when theyre all 
gone im not sure what will happen 
sarie saunders sells unglazed ceramic birds and plant holders 
and small bronze animals at a farm thats been in her family for 
100 years 
peter worsley produces rustic furniture i employed 52 people 
in a twostory factory in johannesburg he said then a 
customer brought me to the crocodile river and i saw what i was 
missing geese charging around the garden dogs playing i had 
lost out on life 
i sold my house and almost everything i had and bought a farm 
here i became a oneman business again and have only 10 people 
working for me now living since then has been total bliss 
</TEXT>
