<TEXT>
the first time louise adams entered a houston hospital for a 
kidney transplant the donated organ ended up being sent halfway 
across the country 
a week later it happened again the kidney her ticket to a 
dialysisfree life was shipped a thousand miles away at the last 
minute 
im sure the person who got it is very deserving but its 
still very disappointing said the 57yearold houston woman 
you find yourself feeling guilty about your feelings because i 
thought well i wouldnt feel quite so badly if it had stayed in 
houston but to ship it out 
she knew she was competing not only with local patients but also 
with those waiting and praying just like her around the country 
one of those waiting and praying was denise warren 27 of 
jordan minn who got the second kidney thanks to new national 
guidelines designed to make transplantation more efficient and 
equitable 
im just happy it happened ms warren said i was 
prepared to be on dialysis for a while i didnt think id get one 
for a long time 
because of an unsuccessful kidney transplant march 16 1986 two 
years to the day before her latest operation denise warrens 
immune system had built up an unusually large number of antibodies 
her best hope was a perfectly matched kidney a rare and therefore 
prized possession 
when such an organ became available in houston in midmarch the 
gulf coast independent organ procurement organization was forced to 
relinquish it under the new rules after a computerized search by 
the united network for organ sharing ms warren was found to be 
the best candidate 
and louise adams was sent home once more to wait her wait 
ended may 20 when she received a new kidney at hermann hospital in 
houston 
thats the way it goes under the 8monthold program which 
requires americas 201 kidney transplant centers and 120 organ 
procurement agencies to share all sixantigen kidneys 
antigens simply are features of alien organisms or tissue that 
can provoke an attack by the immune system if antigens of a 
transplanted organ match those of the recipients body the immune 
system usually does not attack the sixantigen organs only 26 
percent of all donated kidneys had been snapped up where they were 
procured until the new rules were implemented 
the nurses and doctors say its a fair system said ms 
adams of course i can only believe what they tell me 
the kidneysharing policy was adopted last summer by the 
31member board of directors of unos and implemented oct 1 
the virginiabased computer center operates the organ 
procurement transplantation network to which all transplant 
centers must belong to receive medicare reimbursements the network 
was recommended by the national task force on organ 
transplantation formed under the 1984 national transplant act 
unos also instituted a standardized scoring system for 
distributing other increasingly scarce organs like hearts livers 
and lungs patients are awarded points based on medical urgency 
length of time on the waiting list and proximity to the donor 
among other things 
its a great improvement over what existed before which was a 
mishmash of politics and oldboy networks said arthur caplan 
director of the center for biomedical ethics at the university of 
minnesota 
more than 13550 people are awaiting organ transplants in the 
united states 12200 of whom need new kidneys according to arthur 
harrell of the american council on transplantation virtually all 
of the kidney transplant candidates are on dialysis the 
exhausting weekafterweek mechanical elimination of impurities 
from the blood 
to increase the number of nationally shared kidneys and help 
more hardtomatch sensitized patients like ms warren the 
network in march expanded the guidelines to cover certain kidneys 
with fewer than six identified or detected antigens failure to 
comply with any of the guidelines could result in suspension or 
expulsion from the network and loss of medicare funding 
gene pierce executive director of unos expects the change to 
double the number of perfectly matched kidneys unos offers there 
were 115 organ donors reported to unos from oct 1 1987 to april 
30 who matched a potential kidney recipient for all six antigens 
not all were transplanted for various reasons 
whether its sharing kidneys or assigning points the transplant 
surgeon still has the final say according to dr john mcdonald 
president of unos and of the american society of transplant 
surgeons the physician has the option of using his best medical 
judgment now he has to defend that 
the guidelines have not changed what they centers have been 
doing in terms of getting the right organ to the right patient 
because they were doing that anyway he said but it has 
reduced that process to a written policy which they are able to 
follow and defend and argue about 
reaction has been mixed and mcdonald said one cannot have a 
national organization of this type with everybody being perfectly 
happy about it there is no organized group out there that is in 
opposition no rebellion is going on no centers have refused to 
participate and abide by these guidelines 
mandatory kidney sharing has produced the most grumbling 
some experts maintain that the longterm success of kidney 
transplants depends on careful matching of the donor and recipient 
others argue that does not justify flying kidneys all over the 
country since the more they are moved and the longer they go 
unused the less viable they become 
donated kidneys can be preserved outside the body for up to 48 
hours four times longer than livers and nearly 10 times longer 
than hearts 
obviously some people are a little upset when they have to 
send them out they could have used them locally just as well 
pierce said we keep trying to remind them that when you give 
you get back if everyone is cooperating and they must then there 
will be a fair distribution 
brian broznick executive director of the pittsburgh transplant 
foundation winces every time he sends a cadillac kidney out of 
town i do this job because i want to see people transplanted 
period but im a pittsburgher im very proud of the program here 
i want to see this program work i dont want to see my kidneys go 
to waste or share them with everybody 
mary jane lacombe transplant coordinator for the hennepin 
county medical center in minneapolis is ahead of the game as of 
early may she had given up one prized kidney but got back three 
one of which went to ms warren 
broznick had shipped out two perfect kidneys but got only one 
back 
in houston four went out but none came in we provided four 
people with kidneys and a chance they might not have otherwise 
had said rebecca davis executive director of gulf coast on 
the other hand it just so happens that twice the same patient ms 
adams was asked to come in for the potential transplant and twice 
told im sorry we have to ship these kidneys out 
its a very difficult very touchy issue but if you look in 
the global viewpoint were probably doing what is correct 
</TEXT>
