<TEXT>
beach days still turn to deluge with no regard for 
forecasters promises but the tricky art of predicting the weather 
is actually getting better 
how much better so accurate according to one official that 
people are starting to believe them 
its my impression that there is much more reliance on weather 
forecasts today says h robert glahn people will use them 
whereas 20 years ago they probably wouldnt 
there are many statistical ways of interpreting forecasters 
track records says glahn chief of the national weather services 
technologies development laboratory in silver spring md but in 
general studies show that a 48hour forecast now is almost as 
accurate as a 24hour forecast was 20 years ago 
according to the weather services way of keeping time a 
24hour forecast is this mornings prediction of what it will do 
this afternoon a 48hour forecast is todays prediction of what 
will happen tomorrow 
another example of the improvement says glahn is forecasters 
growing avoidance of big errors last winter there was a 6 percent 
chance the weather service would be off 10 degrees or more on 
tomorrows temperature twenty years ago there was a 13 percent 
chance 
other ways of looking at forecasters prowess produce numbers 
that arent quite so impressive 
frederick sanders a meteorologist who retired four years ago 
from the massachusetts institute of technology notes that it isnenough 
to be right most of the time anybody can do that 
in boston for example it rains one day in three so a daily 
forecast of no rain will be right 67 percent of the time in 
yuma ariz it rains just seven days a year making the same 
forecast right 98 percent of the time 
so sanders and others who keep track of such things compare the 
forecast to the average weather whats known as the climatological 
norm 
in boston forecasters give the correct nextday forecast about 
82 percent of the time halfway between 67 percent which requires 
no skill and 100 percent so the forecasters are said to have a 50 
percent skill level 
from 1966 until he retired sanders and his students predicted 
the boston weather every day their accuracy was a little better 
than the weather service and over time he found that their skill 
improved about 5 percent a decade 
a similar analysis by allan h murphy at oregon state university 
found that the weather service is improving 510 percent a decade 
forecasters attribute most of the improvement to computers 
which let them create threedimensional pictures of the atmosphere 
using complex formulas they fastforward the weather to create an 
image of the winds pressures temperatures and moisture in 
tomorrows skies 
i think the improvement in the future will be a little greater 
than it has been says tzvi galchen of the university of 
oklahoma im not willing to bet my house on it but maybe my 
car i have a very old car 
sanders foresees no breakthroughs in forecasting precision but 
he quickly adds that his prediction probably doesnt mean much 
big breakthroughs are always unexpected he says thats 
one of the interesting things about fishing and science 
