the reagan administration has decided against 
offering legislation this year to remove antitrust restrictions on 
the bell telephone companies officials said monday 
although the administration remains convinced the prohibitions 
against bell companies entering certain competitive phone 
businesses should be removed the timing of such a proposal will 
not allow it this year the officials said 
its late into the final year of this congress and they have a 
full plate said james spurlock a spokesman for the national 
telecommunications and information administration a commerce 
department agency 
white house chief of staff howard baker sent a twoparagraph 
memo to members of the cabinetlevel economic policy council saying 
that president reagan decided to stop efforts to persuade congress 
to support legislation that would either relax or remove the 
restrictions according to communicationsweek a trade publication 
which quoted unidentified sources in this weeks issue 
the memo also said the administration had not changed its 
opinion that the restrictions should be lifted the publication 
reported 
white house spokesman bj cooper declined to comment on the 
memo but said there has been a policy decision that we are not 
going to introduce legislation on that topic this year 
the commerce department has been behind the push within the 
administration to allow the bell companies to offer electronic 
information services and manufacture telecommunications equipment 
restrictions prohibiting the companies from entering those 
businesses and from offering longdistance service were imposed by 
the antitrust decree that broke up american telephone amp telegraph 
co in january 1984 
us district judge harold greene who supervises the consent 
decree that broke up atampt last year ruled the bell companies could 
transmit information services but he refused to allow them to 
generate the information itself he said the companies continue to 
control access to local phone networks which would give them an 
unfair advantage over competitors 
