<TEXT>
poor management practices accompanied losses 
that drove the federal land bank in jackson miss into insolvency 
last week a farm credit official said monday 
as of last friday the banks liabilities exceeded its earning 
assets by aproximately 500 million eric p thor president of 
the farm credit assistance board told the senate agriculture 
subcommittee on agricultural credit 
this means that the board of directors and management of the 
bank have lost over 300 million in the past three years he 
added 
thor said sour loans high debt costs and heavy operating costs 
had plagued the bank 
he said the jackson bank sought 410 million to 610 million in 
assistance this year but was unable to come up with a workable plan 
to get out from under 
it seems you have indicated a lot of what you might call poor 
management practices down there said sen john breaux dla 
i would say thats a fair assessment said thor whose board 
was established by congress last year to bail out the ailing farm 
credit system 
lawmakers expressed dismay that the jackson bank had been 
allowed to go downhill until it was beyond rescue they prodded 
officials to avoid any recurrence at other land banks 
we want to avoid another jackson in omaha sen tom daschle 
dsd said 
meanwhile the jackson bank reopened its doors monday to provide 
information to borrowers a key federal regulator expressed hope 
for quick action to restore loan service under supervision of a 
receiver 
we are trying very hard to work out an agreement to restore 
service with the cooperation of some of the other system 
institutions frank w naylor jr told a news conference 
naylor chairman of the farm credit administration stressed 
that the receiver rew enterprises inc of tulsa okla was not 
authorized to make loans to customers of the bank which serves 90 
local lending associations in alabama mississippi and louisiana 
thus it would be necessary to reach an agreement with other farm 
credit system banks to make loans through the receiveroperated 
billiondollar lending cooperative whose doors were closed friday 
afternoon after months of losses averaging 45 million 
such loans would be on an interim basis while the receiver winds 
down the activities of the bank naylor said 
the jackson institution is one of 12 federal land banks within 
the massive farm credit system a 50 billion nationwide network 
of borrowerowned banks and local lending associations the system 
largely unknown to city folk outside the financial industry is a 
longtime bulwark of us agriculture 
doldrums in the farm economy in the early 1980s combined with 
unfavorable credit agreements plus high overhead within the system 
brought some of the banks into hard financial straits in recent 
years that prompted congress to pass a major bailout bill last 
year 
the jackson bank received 30 million in aid under the bailout 
bill but the assistance board that makes such decisions turned off 
the tap last week and instead asked the farm credit administration 
the systems federal regulator to place the institution in 
receivership 
our responsibility will be to wind down the activities of this 
institution naylor said adding that it should take less than a 
year 
naylor was asked if the administrartions action meant there 
soon would be a rash of foreclosures 
quite the contrary he said he said those whose loans are 
not performing would get the full benefit of borrowers rights 
provisions under last years bailout legislation 
the receivers task also would involve placing the banks 
business with other lending institutions naylor said he said it 
was expected that some other system lender would move into the 
threestate area to take over the jackson business but that it was 
too early to say which one 
we would expect fairly quick action he said 
he said it would be legal for the receiver to sell assets to 
private lending institutions but he said the farm credit 
administration certainly will be reviewing all significant 
actions in the district 
nayor said there is evidence of a turnaround for many of the 
farm credit system institutions during the last year there are 
still several land banks facing serious problems but theyre 
working their way through them he added 
the jackson banks porfolio of more than 21000 loans totaled 
168 billion at years end but 40 percent of that amount was tied 
up in loans classified either as nonaccrual or highrisk 
liabilities meanwhile reached 1909 billion on march 31 
